            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="sacred" key="MeterTheou"><name nymRef="Μήτηρ Θεοῦ"><w lemma="μήτηρ"><hi rend="ligature"><expan><abbr rend="supraline">Μ<choice><orig>η</orig><reg>ή</reg></choice></abbr><ex>τη</ex><abbr rend="supraline">ρ</abbr></expan></hi></w>
                    <milestone unit="column" n="right"/><expan><abbr rend="supraline">Θ</abbr><ex>εο</ex><abbr rend="supraline"><choice><orig>υ</orig><reg>ῦ</reg></choice></abbr></expan></name></persName>       
                    <lb n="2"/><choice><orig>Η</orig><reg>Ἡ</reg></choice> <addName type="epithet" key="Eleousa"><choice><orig>Ε</orig><reg>Ἐ</reg></choice>λε <milestone unit="column" n="right"/>οῦσα </addName>         
                 </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
               <p>Pending</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Mother of God, Eleousa</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>Poor condition. Faded. The depiction of the Virgin is directly related to the depiction of Christ on the south pier. Is essentially a dialogue between Virgin and Christ. Virgin the Merciful addresses Christ pleading him to show mercy to the humankind. This representation goes back to the Comnenian art and can be found also in other churches in Cyprus like Panagia tou Arakos at Lagoudera village. It is worth noting that this specific depiction of the Virgin in Cyprus is entitled Ἡ Ἐλεοῦσα, while elsewhere the epithet used is Ἡ Παράκλησις. </p>
            </div>
